INDENG 242A | Offline Report

In-Vehicle Coupon Selection Dashboard

Dataset: In-vehicle Coupon Recommendation | Author: Jingyan Li
Introduction & Methods

Background

  • Objective: Understand customer response to in-vehicle, context-aware coupon recommendations for local businesses.
  • Targeting: Coupons tailored to each user’s current context (destination, time, weather, passengers, etc.).
  • Data Source: Amazon Mechanical Turk survey describing varied driving scenarios.
  • Labeling: Y = 1 for “Drive there right away” or “Later before the coupon expires”; Y = 0 for “No, I do not want the coupon.”
  • Prediction Problem: Given demographic and contextual attributes, predict whether a customer will accept a coupon for a specific venue.

Data Description

in_vehicle_coupon_selection.csv: 12,684 observations, 26 variables.

Key fields include destination, passengers, weather, temperature, time, coupon type, expiration, demographics, income, and visit frequency features (e.g., Bar, CoffeeHouse, CarryAway).

Binary indicators: has_children, toCoupon_GEQ15min, toCoupon_GEQ25min, direction_same.

Categorical variables are one-hot encoded for temperature, destination, passenger, weather, time, coupon, expiration, gender, age, marital status, education, occupation, income, and dining/visit-frequency features.

Methods

Models:
Logistic Regression (baseline)
L1 Logistic Regression (CV-selected λ)
CART (cost-complexity pruned)
Logit + CART ensemble (probability average)
Bagging (200 trees)
Random Forest (300 trees, CV-tuned)
Gradient Boosting (CV-tuned)

Evaluation metrics: Accuracy = (TP + TN)/(Total); TPR = TP/(TP + FN); FPR = FP/(FP + TN); AUC for L1 logit.

Discussion & Conclusion

Feature Importance (Top Drivers)

Offer & Feasibility: Coupon type (Carry-out, Restaurant < $20); Expiration 2h (–); Distance ≥ 15 / 25 min (–); Direction Same (+).

Habits: CoffeeHouse_never, Bar_never (–).

Context / Demographics: Destination = No Urgent Place (+); Time 6 PM (+); Gender = Male, Has Children (– moderate effects).

Discussion

  • Nonlinearity dominates: acceptance rules are interaction-driven.
  • Variance reduction: ensembles suppress overfitting of single trees.
  • Operational impact: bagging reduces false offers ( FPR ↓ 0.1 vs linear models ).
  • Interpretability vs Performance: trade-off between logit clarity and ensemble accuracy.

Limitations

  • Hypothetical survey data (stated vs revealed preferences).
  • Coarse travel-distance thresholds.
  • Single train/test split (not repeated CV).
  • Correlated demographics and habits.
  • Accuracy metric not cost-sensitive.

Practical Implications

  • Personalize by habit before contextual ranking.
  • Adjust thresholds by coupon value or risk of annoyance.
  • Deploy ensemble for prediction; use interpretable model as explanation layer.
  • Extend future work to cost-sensitive and online learning frameworks.
